chunk_content: H “Health workers” refers to individuals involved in safeguarding and contributing to the prevention, S Y promotion, and protection of the health of the population (both professional and auxiliary S professionals). The categories below describe the different types of health workers to be considered T under this indicator. This is not an exhaustive list of all health workers and position titles may vary E M from country to country. For the purposes of this indicator, health workers may include the following S but is not limited to: • Clinical professionals, including doctors, nurses, midwives, laboratory scientists, pharmacists, medical technologists, and psychologists. They usually have a tertiary education, and most countries have a formal method of certifying their qualifications. • Clinical officers, medical and nursing assistants, lab and pharmacy technicians, auxiliary nurses, auxiliary midwives, T&C counselors.
